<br>
I doubt whether an Orion-type ship with &quot;soda-machine&quot; style magazines containing discrete PUs and all the associated handling equipment could ever come close to the kind of mass ratios or simplicity of design that make idea like GCNR, NEP, and NSWR so much more appealing to me.  Especially when comparable ISPs and even thrusts are obtainable with competing technologies.<br>
<br>
In general, I also have a tendency to prefer continuous drives over pulsed drives.  One of the main technical challenges with the Orion project was the design of shock absorbers to reduce acceleration felt by the main ship to tolerable levels(down from the thousands of Gs experienced by the pusher).  Even if these absorbers can be built.  The ride will still be bumpy.  And in the reference designs the shocks took up more than 25% of total ship mass.  That is mass that a NSWR could have available as free payload.<br>
<br>
Despite claims to the contrary, Orion is one of the most complex drive mechanisms around.  Having a huge magazine of nukes that have to be individually loaded and fired through a thousand ton pusher plate that is flying back and forth through 5 meters every half a second just seems like asking for trouble. <br>
<br>
Simplicity is good. Simplicity means low cost, low failure rate and longer life cycle.  To me, competing ideas like NSWR and GCNR offer comparable or better performance to Orion in a much simpler, more lightweight, more scalable package. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tachyon Wrangler</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/19/03 6:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=155>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/images/offedge.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Orion</span><hr size=1> Just to address one small part of the above...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
This is just my personal bias, but it seems to me that using liquid propellents that can be stored in tanks and moved to the right place at the right time by pipes and pumps makes the entire idea of propelling spacecraft a lot simpler...<br>
