<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> I never said Orion didn't have some issues to be looked at.<br>
I however am not assuming that the Orion designers were<br>
1) evil conspirators, hiding their inability to make a workable design<br>
2) complete ignoramuses, totally unable to understand the nature of the environment they were proposiong to operate in</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I’m not saying that either. They may have thought they had a great idea on paper. And when they continued to overcome the engineering difficulties with more improved ideas, their zeal and enthusiasm increased in magnitude – that’s just human nature. But this enthusiasm overshadowed some very important problems that they knew could not be properly tested due to the obvious logistics. Once the NASA scientists began to look at the project from their unbiased perspective, these problems became glaringly obvious, hence the project was killed.<br>
<br>
Perhaps Dyson and Co. knew there were great risks and many unknowns involved, but they were willing to continue trying no matter what the consequences. A lot of Orions could have been built and flown with disastrous results. They may have eventually come up with a design that would work, but I am still very skeptical to that notion. I think many here are not skeptical enough and seem to be caught up in the same zeal and enthusiasm.<br>
<br>
How many V2’s were built and tested before they finally got it right?<br>
