<br>
There was an interview of Dr. Finger in the December 2002 issue of Nuclear News. Dr. Finger was head of the NASA group responible for reviewing the ORION project and advising his superiors at NASA as to whether to pick up the project, if anyone knows why NASA did not continue it, he would. The interviewer asked Finger about ORION and he told him that he thought the people working on it were brilliant individuals, and that the reason he advised NASA not to take up the project was based on worries related to developing a working engine using the ground testing methods traditionaly used by NASA, and the political problems of NASA ground testing nuclear devices. It was not dropped because of fears that the concept would not work. He also mentioned that the people at General ATomic told him that not all the problems with the pusher plate were solved, but didn't think it would have killed the project. Real experimental testing would have been needed to try to correct any problems.<br>
<br>
And as to how the plasma would be kept from moving down the tube, they had a shield covering the tube which could be opened to let the PU's be shot out. One advantage of using any pulsed propulsion system in space (ORION, ICAN, Daedales, etc.) is that you don't have to run it at the same rate you would as a launcher. The pulse rate could be slowed down as far as you want, it simply extends the acceleration rate.<br>
